From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: nix-on-z <nix-on-z@s390x>
Date: Fri, 17 Apr 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] Fix wide_integer tuple construction limb order on big-endian

wide_integer_from_tuple_like stores tuple element i into items[i], but
the canonical storage layout indexes limbs low-to-high via little(i):
  little(i) = i                         (on little-endian)
  little(i) = item_count - 1 - i        (on big-endian)

On little-endian these coincide, so the bug is invisible. On big-endian
it stores tuple[0] (intended as the lowest limb) into items[0], which
is the HIGHEST position — the low/high halves of the wide integer get
swapped.

This shows up for any code that constructs a wide integer from a tuple
or initializer_list longer than one element (Int128{low, high}, etc.).
Symptom on s390x: Int128{1, 1} produced 2^64 + 1 instead of 2^64, and
conversely. Note that the multi-element initializer_list path at lines
1288–1299 already uses items[little(i)] — this patch aligns tuple_like
with that correct pattern.

The cityhash caller previously compensated by pre-swapping the pair on
BE; with the function now correct, both endianness branches pass
(low64, high64) and the branch can be collapsed.

On little-endian: little(i) == i, so the generated code is unchanged.
---
--- a/base/base/wide_integer_impl.h
+++ b/base/base/wide_integer_impl.h
@@ -387,9 +387,9 @@
         if constexpr (i < item_count)
         {
             if constexpr (i < std::tuple_size_v<TupleLike>)
-                self.items[i] = std::get<i>(tuple);
+                self.items[little(i)] = std::get<i>(tuple);
             else
-                self.items[i] = 0;
+                self.items[little(i)] = 0;
             wide_integer_from_tuple_like<TupleLike, i + 1>(self, tuple);
         }
     }
@@ -399,10 +399,9 @@
     {
         static_assert(sizeof(item_count) >= 2);

-        if constexpr (std::endian::native == std::endian::little)
-            wide_integer_from_tuple_like(self, std::make_pair(value.low64, value.high64));
-        else
-            wide_integer_from_tuple_like(self, std::make_pair(value.high64, value.low64));
+        /// Pass limbs in low-to-high order; wide_integer_from_tuple_like maps them
+        /// through little(i) so the BE/LE paths produce the same in-memory layout.
+        wide_integer_from_tuple_like(self, std::make_pair(value.low64, value.high64));
     }

     /**
